<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="406" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,732,1012]" pageId="5" pageNumber="406">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,804,831]" pageId="5" pageNumber="406">Distribution.</emphasis>
This is the first record from 
<collectingCountry box="[666,810,805,831]" name="Saudi Arabia" pageId="5" pageNumber="406">Saudi Arabia</collectingCountry>
and Arabian Peninsula. This species was described from 
<collectingCountry box="[151,240,841,867]" name="Sweden" pageId="5" pageNumber="406">Sweden</collectingCountry>
(Uplandia and Esperöd). Widespread in Europe, from southern 
<collectingCountry box="[959,1048,841,867]" name="Sweden" pageId="5" pageNumber="406">Sweden</collectingCountry>
to North Africa and east to 
<collectingCountry box="[1361,1436,841,867]" name="Russia" pageId="5" pageNumber="406">Russia</collectingCountry>
and the Caucasus, it is also recorded from 
<collectingCountry box="[640,707,877,903]" name="Japan" pageId="5" pageNumber="406">Japan</collectingCountry>
. It is also known from Nearctic 
<collectingCountry box="[1078,1166,877,903]" name="Canada" pageId="5" pageNumber="406">Canada</collectingCountry>
. In Britain, it is usually found on dunes where its larvae develop in dead snails.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
